        <h4>Evaluating Binance's Security Posture</h4>
        <p>Binance's security is a nuanced topic. They've invested heavily in technical security while facing significant regulatory challenges. Here's our detailed assessment.</p>

        <h5>The SAFU Fund Explained</h5>
        <p>The Secure Asset Fund for Users (SAFU) holds approximately $1 billion in assets (primarily BTC, BNB, and stablecoins) to cover potential losses from security breaches. This was established after Binance's 2019 hack where 7,000 BTC was stolen. The fund successfully covered user losses in that incident. However, SAFU is not regulated insurance - it's Binance's voluntary commitment. Its effectiveness depends on Binance's continued solvency and willingness to use it.</p>

        <h5>Technical Security Assessment</h5>
        <p>On the technical side, Binance performs well: cold storage for majority of assets, mandatory 2FA, address whitelisting, anti-phishing codes, and device management. They employ a large security team and have bug bounty programs. The 2019 hack exploited user-level vulnerabilities (phishing, API key theft) rather than core platform security. Since then, no major security breaches have occurred on the main platform.</p>

        <h5>Regulatory Status Reality</h5>
        <p>Binance's regulatory situation is complicated. They're registered/licensed in France (AMF), Italy (OAM), Spain, and several other jurisdictions. However, they've faced enforcement from US regulators (DOJ, SEC, CFTC), UK FCA, and others. The $4.3 billion settlement in 2023 resolved major US issues, but ongoing scrutiny continues. For users, this means: check if Binance operates legally in your jurisdiction, understand that services may be restricted or changed, and consider the counterparty risk of using a platform with regulatory uncertainty.</p>

        <h5>Our Security Recommendation</h5>
        <p>For active trading, Binance's security is adequate. For long-term holding, we recommend withdrawing to personal wallets rather than keeping significant assets on any exchange. Enable all available security features (2FA via authenticator app, not SMS), use address whitelisting, and never share API keys with full withdrawal permissions. The principle "not your keys, not your coins" applies regardless of exchange security.</p>
