        <h5>Spot vs Futures: When to Use Each</h5>
        <p>Spot trading (buying actual crypto) is straightforward: you own the asset, can withdraw it, and profit/loss is 1:1 with price movement. Futures trading uses contracts that track price but offer leverage (up to 125x) - you can control large positions with small capital, but losses are amplified equally. Our guidance: beginners should stick to spot. Futures are for experienced traders with strict risk management. The majority of retail futures traders lose money.</p>

        <h5>The Altcoin Advantage</h5>
        <p>Binance lists more cryptocurrencies (350+) than any major competitor. New projects often list on Binance first or exclusively. For altcoin traders seeking early access to emerging tokens, this is Binance's killer feature. However, more listings also mean more potential scams and failed projects - do your own research before buying obscure tokens.</p>

        <h5>Binance Earn: The Yield Options</h5>
        <p>Binance Earn offers multiple ways to earn yield: Flexible Savings (withdraw anytime, lower APY), Locked Staking (fixed term, higher APY), Launchpool (stake to earn new tokens), and DeFi Staking. APYs vary significantly - BTC/ETH offer 1-5% while stablecoins can reach 5-10%. Remember: these yields come with risk (smart contract, counterparty, token price). They're not equivalent to bank interest.</p>

        <h5>Order Types and Execution</h5>
